6. Attractors, traps, and basins

This is where it gets powerful.

Some concepts or narratives act like attractors:
thought tends to organize around them.

Examples:
	•	identity
	•	survival
	•	status
	•	fairness
	•	betrayal
	•	novelty

Some are traps:
they pull thought in but degrade precision.

Examples:
	•	vague buzzwords
	•	aesthetic-only metaphors
	•	identity capture
	•	local coherence without invariants

The Atlas should display:
	•	attractor strength
	•	trap risk
	•	escape routes
	•	stabilizing counterweights

This would be incredibly useful for both humans and AI.

⸻

7. Contradiction tears and stress lines

Contradictions should not just be red text in a list.
They should be visible as tears or stress fractures in the map.

Examples:
	•	a concept claiming incompatible properties in same domain/time
	•	an analogy transported without bridge operator
	•	an abstraction that erased load-bearing detail

Stress lines show where a framework is under strain.

This lets reasoning failure become spatially inspectable.

⸻

8. Narrative currents

Stories are not just labels on nodes.
Stories create flow.

A narrative current is a directional bias in the space.

Examples:
	•	redemption arc current
	•	decline/fall current
	•	zero-sum conflict current
	•	growth-through-trial current

These currents change what moves feel natural.

So the Atlas should be able to show:
	•	which narratives are currently shaping a region
	•	which alternatives exist
	•	what new trajectories appear if the field changes

This would make narrative engineering legible.

⸻

9. Memory paths and retrieval routes

This solves a real problem.

People forget because they stored content in one form with one path.

The Atlas should preserve multiple routes to the same region:
	•	definition route
	•	story route
	•	image route
	•	analogy route
	•	equation route
	•	example route
	•	emotional anchor route

That means one idea can be re-entered from many directions.

This is how strong memory actually works.

